# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: microgrid-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration is a more efficient use of fuel or heat, because otherwise-wasted heat from electricity generation is put to some productive use.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Combined heat and power (CHP) plants recover otherwise wasted thermal energy for heating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This is also called combined heat and power district heating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Small CHP plants are an example of decentralized energy.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] By-product heat at moderate temperatures (100–180 °C (212–356 °F) can also be used in absorption refrigerators for cooling.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The supply of high-temperature heat first drives a gas or steam turbine-powered generator.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The resulting low-temperature waste heat is then used for water or space heating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] At smaller scales (typically below 1 MW), a gas engine or diesel engine may be used.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration is also common with geothermal power plants as they often produce relatively low grade heat, sometimes binary cycles may be necessary to reach an acceptable thermal efficiency for generating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration is less commonly employed in nuclear power plants as NIMBY and safety considerations have often kept them further from population centers than comparable chemical power plants and district heating is less efficient in lower population density areas due to transmission losses.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration was practiced in some of the earliest installations of electrical generation.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Before central stations distributed power, industries generating their own power used exhaust steam for process heating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Large office and apartment buildings, hotels, and stores commonly generated their own power and used waste steam for building heat.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Due to the high cost of early purchased power, these CHP operations continued for many years after utility electricity became available.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Many process industries, such as chemical plants, oil refineries and pulp and paper mills, require large amounts of process heat for such operations as chemical reactors, distillation columns, steam driers and other uses.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This heat, which is usually used in the form of steam, can be generated at the typically low pressures used in heating, or can be generated at much higher pressure and passed through a turbine first to generate electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In the turbine the steam pressure and temperature is lowered as the internal energy of the steam is converted to work.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The lower-pressure steam leaving the turbine can then be used for process heat.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Steam turbines at thermal power stations are normally designed to be fed high-pressure steam, which exits the turbine at a condenser operating a few degrees above ambient temperature and at a few millimeters of mercury absolute pressure.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] (This is called a *condensing* turbine.) For all practical purposes this steam has negligible useful energy before it is condensed.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Steam turbines for cogeneration are designed for *extraction* of some steam at lower pressures after it has passed through a number of turbine stages, with the un-extracted steam going on through the turbine to a condenser.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In this case, the extracted steam causes a mechanical power loss in the downstream stages of the turbine.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Or they are designed, with or without extraction, for final exhaust at *back pressure* (non-condensing).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The extracted or exhaust steam is used for process heating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Steam at ordinary process heating conditions still has a considerable amount of enthalpy that could be used for power generation, so cogeneration has an opportunity cost.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A typical power generation turbine in a paper mill may have extraction pressures of 160 and 60 psi (1.10 and 0.41 MPa).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A typical back pressure may be 60 psi (0.41 MPa).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In practice these pressures are custom designed for each facility.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Conversely, simply generating process steam for industrial purposes instead of high enough pressure to generate power at the top end also has an opportunity cost (See: Steam supply and exhaust conditions).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The capital and operating cost of high-pressure boilers, turbines, and generators is substantial.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This equipment is normally operated continuously, which usually limits self-generated power to large-scale operations.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A combined cycle (in which several thermodynamic cycles produce electricity), may also be used to extract heat using a heating system as condenser of the power plant's bottoming cycle.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] For example, the RU-25 MHD generator in Moscow heated a boiler for a conventional steam powerplant, whose condensate was then used for space heat.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A more modern system might use a gas turbine powered by natural gas, whose exhaust powers a steam plant, whose condensate provides heat.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration plants based on a combined cycle power unit can have thermal efficiencies above 80%.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The viability of CHP (sometimes termed utilisation factor), especially in smaller CHP installations, depends on a good baseload of operation, both in terms of an on-site (or near site) electrical demand and heat demand.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In practice, an exact match between the heat and electricity needs rarely exists.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A CHP plant can either meet the need for heat (*heat driven operation*) or be run as a power plant with some use of its waste heat, the latter being less advantageous in terms of its utilisation factor and thus its overall efficiency.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The viability can be greatly increased where opportunities for trigeneration exist.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In such cases, the heat from the CHP plant is also used as a primary energy source to deliver cooling by means of an absorption chiller.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] CHP is most efficient when heat can be used on-site or very close to it.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Overall efficiency is reduced when the heat must be transported over longer distances.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This requires heavily insulated pipes, which are expensive and inefficient; whereas electricity can be transmitted along a comparatively simple wire, and over much longer distances for the same energy loss.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A car engine becomes a CHP plant in winter when the reject heat is useful for warming the interior of the vehicle.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The example illustrates the point that deployment of CHP depends on heat uses in the vicinity of the heat engine.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Thermally enhanced oil recovery (TEOR) plants often produce a substantial amount of excess electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] After generating electricity, these plants pump leftover steam into heavy oil wells so that the oil will flow more easily, increasing production.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration plants are commonly found in district heating systems of cities, central heating systems of larger buildings (e.g. hospitals, hotels, prisons) and are commonly used in the industry in thermal production processes for process water, cooling, steam production or CO2 fertilization.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Topping cycle plants primarily produce electricity from a steam turbine.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Partly expanded steam is then condensed in a heating condensor at a temperature level that is suitable e.g. district heating or water desalination.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Bottoming cycle plants produce high temperature heat for industrial processes, then a waste heat recovery boiler feeds an electrical plant.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Bottoming cycle plants are only used in industrial processes that require very high temperatures such as furnaces for glass and metal manufacturing, so they are less common.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Large cogeneration systems provide heating water and power for an industrial site or an entire town.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Smaller cogeneration units may use a reciprocating engine or Stirling engine.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The heat is removed from the exhaust and radiator.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The systems are popular in small sizes because small gas and diesel engines are less expensive than small gas- or oil-fired steam-electric plants.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Some cogeneration plants are fired by biomass, or industrial and municipal solid waste (see incineration).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Some CHP plants use waste gas as the fuel for electricity and heat generation.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Waste gases can be gas from animal waste, landfill gas, gas from coal mines, sewage gas, and combustible industrial waste gas.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Some cogeneration plants combine gas and solar photovoltaic generation to further improve technical and environmental performance.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Such hybrid systems can be scaled down to the building level and even individual homes.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Micro combined heat and power or 'Micro cogeneration" is a so-called distributed energy resource (DER).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The installation is usually less than 5 kWe in a house or small business.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Instead of burning fuel to merely heat space or water, some of the energy is converted to electricity in addition to heat.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This electricity can be used within the home or business or, if permitted by the grid management, sold back into the electric power grid.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Delta-ee consultants stated in 2013 that with 64% of global sales the fuel cell micro-combined heat and power passed the conventional systems in sales in 2012.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] 20,000 units were sold in Japan in 2012 overall within the Ene Farm project.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] For PEM fuel cell units, which shut down at night, this equates to an estimated lifetime of between ten and fifteen years.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] For a price of $22,600 before installation.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] For 2013 a state subsidy for 50,000 units is in place.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] MicroCHP installations use five different technologies: microturbines, internal combustion engines like BHPPs, stirling engines, closed-cycle steam engines, and fuel cells.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] One author indicated in 2008 that MicroCHP based on Stirling engines is the most cost-effective of the so-called microgeneration technologies in abating carbon emissions.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A 2013 UK report from Ecuity Consulting stated that MCHP is the most cost-effective method of using gas to generate energy at the domestic level.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] However, advances in reciprocation engine technology are adding efficiency to CHP plants, particularly in the biogas field.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] As both MiniCHP and CHP have been shown to reduce emissions they could play a large role in the field of CO2 reduction from buildings, where more than 14% of emissions can be saved using CHP in buildings.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The University of Cambridge reported a cost-effective steam engine MicroCHP prototype in 2017 which has the potential to be commercially competitive in the following decades.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Quite recently, in some private homes, fuel cell micro-CHP plants can now be found, which can operate on hydrogen, or other fuels as natural gas or LPG.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] When running on natural gas, it relies on steam reforming of natural gas to convert the natural gas to hydrogen prior to use in the fuel cell.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This hence still emits CO2 (see reaction) but (temporarily) running on this can be a good solution until the point where the hydrogen is starting to be distributed through the (natural gas) piping system.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Another MicroCHP example is a natural gas or propane fueled Electricity Producing Condensing Furnace.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] It combines the fuel saving technique of cogeneration meaning producing electric power and useful heat from a single source of combustion.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The condensing furnace is a forced-air gas system with a secondary heat exchanger that allows heat to be extracted from combustion products down to the ambient temperature along with recovering heat from the water vapor.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The chimney is replaced by a water drain and vent to the side of the building.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A plant producing electricity, heat and cold is called a trigeneration or polygeneration plant.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration systems linked to absorption chillers or adsorption chillers use waste heat for refrigeration.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In the United States, Consolidated Edison distributes 66 billion kilograms of 350 °F (177 °C) steam each year through its seven cogeneration plants to 100,000 buildings in Manhattan—the biggest steam district in the United States.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The peak delivery is 10 million pounds per hour (or approximately 2.5 GW).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration is still common in pulp and paper mills, refineries and chemical plants.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In this "industrial cogeneration/CHP", the heat is typically recovered at higher temperatures (above 100 °C) and used for process steam or drying duties.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This is more valuable and flexible than low-grade waste heat, but there is a slight loss of power generation.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The increased focus on sustainability has made industrial CHP more attractive, as it substantially reduces carbon footprint compared to generating steam or burning fuel on-site and importing electric power from the grid.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Smaller industrial co-generation units have an output capacity of 5–25 MW and represent a viable off-grid option for a variety of remote applications to reduce carbon emissions.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Industrial cogeneration plants normally operate at much lower boiler pressures than utilities.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Utilities are typically larger scale power than industry, which helps offset the higher capital costs of high pressure.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Utilities are less likely to have sharp load swings than industrial operations, which deal with shutting down or starting up units that may represent a significant percent of either steam or power demand.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A heat recovery steam generator (HRSG) is a steam boiler that uses hot exhaust gases from the gas turbines or reciprocating engines in a CHP plant to heat up water and generate steam.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The steam, in turn, drives a steam turbine or is used in industrial processes that require heat.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Biomass refers to any plant or animal matter in which it is possible to be reused as a source of heat or electricity, such as sugarcane, vegetable oils, wood, organic waste and residues from the food or agricultural industries.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Brazil is now considered a world reference in terms of energy generation from biomass.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A growing sector in the use of biomass for power generation is the sugar and alcohol sector, which mainly uses sugarcane bagasse as fuel for thermal and electric power generation.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In the sugarcane industry, cogeneration is fueled by the bagasse residue of sugar refining, which is burned to produce steam.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Some steam can be sent through a turbine that turns a generator, producing electric power.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Energy cogeneration in sugarcane industries located in Brazil is a practice that has been growing in last years.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] With the adoption of energy cogeneration in the sugar and alcohol sector, the sugarcane industries are able to supply the electric energy demand needed to operate, and generate a surplus that can be commercialized.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In comparison with the electric power generation by means of fossil fuel-based thermoelectric plants, such as natural gas, the energy generation using sugarcane bagasse has environmental advantages due to the reduction of CO2 emissions.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In addition to the environmental advantages, cogeneration using sugarcane bagasse presents advantages in terms of efficiency comparing to thermoelectric generation, through the final destination of the energy produced.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] While in thermoelectric generation, part of the heat produced is lost, in cogeneration this heat has the possibility of being used in the production processes, increasing the overall efficiency of the process.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In sugarcane cultivation, is usually used potassium source's containing high concentration of chlorine, such as potassium chloride (KCl).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Considering that KCl is applied in huge quantities, sugarcane ends up absorbing high concentrations of chlorine.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This leads to dioxins and methyl chloride being emitted when the sugarcane bagasse is burned.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Dioxins are highly toxic and carcinogenic, whilst methyl chloride causes significant ozone depletion.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] A heat pump may be compared with a CHP unit as follows.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Typically for every unit of electrical power lost, then about 6 units of heat are made available at about 90 °C (194 °F).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Thus CHP has an effective Coefficient of Performance (COP) compared to a heat pump of 6.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] However, for a remotely operated heat pump, losses in the electrical distribution network would need to be considered, of the order of 6%.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] It is also possible to run a heat driven operation combined with a heat pump, where the excess electricity (as heat demand is the defining factor on se) is used to drive a heat pump.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] As heat demand increases, more electricity is generated to drive the heat pump, with the waste heat also heating the heating fluid.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] As the efficiency of heat pumps depends on the difference between hot end and cold end temperature (efficiency rises as the difference decreases) it may be worthwhile to combine even relatively low grade waste heat otherwise unsuitable for home heating with heat pumps.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] For example, a large enough reservoir of cooling water at 15 °C (59 °F) can significantly improve efficiency of heat pumps drawing from such a reservoir compared to air source heat pumps drawing from cold air during a −20 °C (−4 °F) night.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In the summer when there's both demand for air conditioning and warm water, the same water may even serve as both a "dump" for the waste heat rejected by a/c units and as a "source" for heat pumps providing warm water.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Those considerations are behind what is sometimes called "cold district heating" using a "heat" source whose temperature is well below those usually employed in district heating.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Most industrial countries generate the majority of their electrical power needs in large centralized facilities with capacity for large electrical power output.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] These plants benefit from economy of scale, but may need to transmit electricity across long distances causing transmission losses.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration or trigeneration production is subject to limitations in the local demand and thus may sometimes need to reduce (e.g., heat or cooling production to match the demand).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] An example of cogeneration with trigeneration applications in a major city is the New York City steam system.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Every heat engine is subject to the theoretical efficiency limits of the Carnot cycle or subset Rankine cycle in the case of steam turbine power plants or Brayton cycle in gas turbine with steam turbine plants.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Most of the efficiency loss with steam power generation is associated with the latent heat of vaporization of steam that is not recovered when a turbine exhausts its low temperature and pressure steam to a condenser.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The majority of this heat is from the latent heat of vaporization when the steam condenses.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Heat output may also be used for cooling (for example, in summer), thanks to an absorption chiller.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Typical cogeneration models have losses as in any system.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Conventional central coal- or nuclear-powered power stations convert about 33–45% of their input heat to electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Brayton cycle power plants operate at up to 60% efficiency.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In the case of conventional power plants, approximately 10-15% of this heat is lost up the stack of the boiler.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Most of the remaining heat emerges from the turbines as low-grade waste heat with no significant local uses, so it is usually rejected to the environment, typically to cooling water passing through a condenser.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Because turbine exhaust is normally just above ambient temperature, some potential power generation is sacrificed in rejecting higher-temperature steam from the turbine for cogeneration purposes.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] For cogeneration to be practical power generation and end use of heat must be in relatively close proximity (<2 km typically).
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Even though the efficiency of a small distributed electrical generator may be lower than a large central power plant, the use of its waste heat for local heating and cooling can result in an overall use of the primary fuel supply as great as 80%.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This provides substantial financial and environmental benefits.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Typically, for a gas-fired plant the fully installed cost per kW electrical is around £400/kW (US$577), which is comparable with large central power stations.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The EU has actively incorporated cogeneration into its energy policy via the CHP Directive.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This directive intends to support cogeneration and establish a method for calculating cogeneration abilities per country.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The development of cogeneration has been very uneven over the years and has been dominated throughout the last decades by national circumstances.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The European Union generates 11% of its electricity using cogeneration.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] However, there is large difference between Member States with variations of the energy savings between 2% and 60%.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Europe has the three countries with the world's most intensive cogeneration economies: Denmark, the Netherlands and Finland.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Of the 28.46 TWh of electrical power generated by conventional thermal power plants in Finland in 2012, 81.80% was cogeneration.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Other European countries are also making great efforts to increase efficiency.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Germany reported that at present, over 50% of the country's total electricity demand could be provided through cogeneration.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] So far, Germany has set the target to double its electricity cogeneration from 12.5% of the country's electricity to 25% of the country's electricity by 2020 and has passed supporting legislation accordingly.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The UK is also actively supporting combined heat and power.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In light of UK's goal to achieve a 60% reduction in carbon dioxide emissions by 2050, the government has set the target to source at least 15% of its government electricity use from CHP by 2010.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Other UK measures to encourage CHP growth are financial incentives, grant support, a greater regulatory framework, and government leadership and partnership.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] According to the IEA 2008 modeling of cogeneration expansion for the G8 countries, the expansion of cogeneration in France, Germany, Italy and the UK alone would effectively double the existing primary fuel savings by 2030.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] This would increase Europe's savings from today's 155.69 Twh to 465 Twh in 2030.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] It would also result in a 16% to 29% increase in each country's total cogenerated electricity by 2030.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Governments are being assisted in their CHP endeavors by organizations like COGEN Europe who serve as an information hub for the most recent updates within Europe's energy policy.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] COGEN is Europe's umbrella organization representing the interests of the cogeneration industry.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The European public–private partnership Fuel Cells and Hydrogen Joint Undertaking Seventh Framework Programme project ene.field deploys in 2017 up 1,000 residential fuel cell Combined Heat and Power (micro-CHP) installations in 12 states.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Per 2012 the first 2 installations have taken place.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] In the United Kingdom, the *Combined Heat and Power Quality Assurance* scheme regulates the combined production of heat and power.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] It defines, through calculation of inputs and outputs, "Good Quality CHP" in terms of the achievement of primary energy savings against conventional separate generation of heat and electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Compliance with Combined Heat and Power Quality Assurance is required for cogeneration installations to be eligible for government subsidies and tax incentives.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Perhaps the first modern use of energy recycling was done by Thomas Edison.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] His 1882 Pearl Street Station, the world's first commercial power plant, was a combined heat and power plant, producing both electricity and thermal energy while using waste heat to warm neighboring buildings.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Recycling allowed Edison's plant to achieve approximately 50 percent efficiency.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] By the early 1900s, regulations emerged to promote rural electrification through the construction of centralized plants managed by regional utilities.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] These regulations not only promoted electrification throughout the countryside, but they also discouraged decentralized power generation, such as cogeneration.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] By 1978, Congress recognized that efficiency at central power plants had stagnated and sought to encourage improved efficiency with the Public Utility Regulatory Policies Act (PURPA), which encouraged utilities to buy power from other energy producers.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Cogeneration plants proliferated, soon producing about 8% of all energy in the United States.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] However, the bill left implementation and enforcement up to individual states, resulting in little or nothing being done in many parts of the country.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The United States Department of Energy has an aggressive goal of having CHP constitute 20% of generation capacity by 2030.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] Eight Clean Energy Application Centers have been established across the nation.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] The focus of the Application Centers is to provide an outreach and technology deployment program for end users, policymakers, utilities, and industry stakeholders.
[src:microgrid-control/combined-heat-and-power] High electric rates in New England and the Middle Atlantic make these areas of the United States the most beneficial for cogeneration.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Conventional power stations, such as coal-fired, gas, and nuclear powered plants, as well as hydroelectric dams and large-scale solar power stations, are centralized and often require electric energy to be transmitted over long distances.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] By contrast, DER systems are decentralized, modular, and more flexible technologies that are located close to the load they serve, albeit having capacities of only 10 megawatts (MW) or less.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] These systems can comprise multiple generation and storage components; in this instance, they are referred to as hybrid power systems.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] DER systems typically use renewable energy sources, including small hydro, biomass, biogas, solar power, wind power, and geothermal power, and increasingly play an important role for the electric power distribution system.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A grid-connected device for electricity storage can also be classified as a DER system and is often called a **distributed energy storage system** (**DESS**).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] By means of an interface, DER systems can be managed and coordinated within a smart grid.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed generation and storage enables the collection of energy from many sources and may lower environmental impacts and improve the security of supply.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] One of the major issues with the integration of the DER such as solar power, wind power, etc. is the uncertain nature of such electricity resources.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Microgrids are modern, localized, small-scale grids, contrary to the traditional, centralized electricity grid (macrogrid).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Microgrids can disconnect from the centralized grid and operate autonomously, strengthen grid resilience, and help mitigate grid disturbances.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] They are typically low-voltage AC grids, often use diesel generators, and are installed by the community they serve.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Microgrids increasingly employ a mixture of different distributed energy resources, such as solar hybrid power systems, which significantly reduce the amount of carbon emitted.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Historically, central plants have been an integral part of the electric grid, in which large generating facilities are specifically located either close to resources or otherwise located far from populated load centers.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] These, in turn, supply the traditional transmission and distribution (T&D) grid that distributes bulk power to load centers and from there to consumers.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] These were developed when the costs of transporting fuel and integrating generating technologies into populated areas far exceeded the cost of developing T&D facilities and tariffs.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Central plants are usually designed to take advantage of available economies of scale in a site-specific manner, and are built as "one-off", custom projects.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Thus, the grid had become the main driver of remote customers' power costs and power quality problems, which became more acute as digital equipment required extremely reliable electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Efficiency gains no longer come from increasing generating capacity, but from smaller units located closer to sites of demand.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] For example, coal power plants are built away from cities to prevent their heavy air pollution from affecting the populace.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In addition, such plants are often built near collieries to minimize the cost of transporting coal.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Hydroelectric plants are by their nature limited to operating at sites with sufficient water flow.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Low pollution is a crucial advantage of combined cycle plants that burn natural gas.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The low pollution permits the plants to be near enough to a city to provide district heating and cooling.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed energy resources are mass-produced, small, and less site-specific.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Along with higher relative prices for energy, higher overall complexity and total costs for regulatory oversight, tariff administration, and metering and billing.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Capital markets have come to realize that right-sized resources, for individual customers, distribution substations, or microgrids, are able to offer important but little-known economic advantages over central plants.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Smaller units achieved greater economic benefits through mass-production than larger units gained from their size alone.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The increased value of these resources—resulting from improvements in financial risk, engineering flexibility, security, and environmental quality—often outweighs their apparent cost disadvantages.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed generation (DG), vis-à-vis central plants, must be justified on a life-cycle basis.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Unfortunately, many of the direct, and virtually all of the indirect, benefits of DG are not captured within traditional utility cash-flow accounting.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] While the levelized cost of DG is typically more expensive than conventional, centralized sources on a kilowatt-hour basis, this does not consider negative aspects of conventional fuels.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The additional premium for DG is rapidly declining as demand increases and technology progresses, and sufficient and reliable demand may bring economies of scale, innovation, competition, and more flexible financing, that could make DG clean energy part of a more diversified future.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] DG reduces the amount of energy lost in transmitting electricity because the electricity is generated very near where it is used, perhaps even in the same building.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This also reduces the size and number of power lines that must be constructed.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Typical DER systems in a feed-in tariff (FIT) scheme have low maintenance, low pollution and high efficiencies.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In the past, these traits required dedicated operating engineers and large complex plants to reduce pollution.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] However, modern embedded systems can provide these traits with automated operation and renewable energy, such as solar, wind and geothermal.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This reduces the size of power plant that can show a profit.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In November 2024 Deye and Sol-Ark inverter manufacturer remotely disabled in some countries due to alleged regional sales policy dispute.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The companies later claimed the blockage was not remote but due to geofencing mechanisms built into the inverters.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] EU NIS2 directive expands the cybersecurity requirements to the energy generation market, which has faced backlash from renewable energy lobby groups.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Grid parity occurs when an alternative energy source can generate electricity at a levelized cost (LCOE) that is less than or equal to the end consumer's retail price.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Reaching grid parity is considered to be the point at which an energy source becomes a contender for widespread development without subsidies or government support.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Since the 2010s, grid parity for solar and wind has become a reality in a growing number of markets, including Australia, several European countries, and some states in the U.S.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed energy resource (**DER**) systems are small-scale power generation or storage technologies (typically in the range of 1 kW to 10,000 kW) used to provide an alternative to or an enhancement of the traditional electric power system.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] DER systems typically are characterized by high initial capital costs per kilowatt.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] DER systems also serve as storage device and are often called *Distributed energy storage systems* (DESS).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed cogeneration sources use steam turbines, natural gas-fired fuel cells, microturbines or reciprocating engines to turn generators.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The hot exhaust is then used for space or water heating, or to drive an absorptive chiller for cooling such as air-conditioning.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In addition to natural gas-based schemes, distributed energy projects can also include other renewable or low carbon fuels including biofuels, biogas, landfill gas, sewage gas, coal bed methane, syngas and associated petroleum gas.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Delta-ee consultants stated in 2013 that with 64% of global sales, the fuel cell micro combined heat and power passed the conventional systems in sales in 2012.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] 20.000 units were sold in Japan in 2012 overall within the Ene Farm project.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] With a Lifetime of around 60,000 hours for PEM fuel cell units, which shut down at night, this equates to an estimated lifetime of between ten and fifteen years.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In addition, molten carbonate fuel cell and solid oxide fuel cells using natural gas, such as the ones from FuelCell Energy and the Bloom energy server, or waste-to-energy processes such as the Gate 5 Energy System are used as a distributed energy resource.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Photovoltaics uses solar cells assembled into solar panels to convert sunlight into electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] It is a growing technology, doubling its worldwide installed capacity every couple of years.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] PV systems range from distributed, residential, and commercial rooftop or building integrated installations, to large, centralized utility-scale photovoltaic power stations.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The predominant PV technology is crystalline silicon, while thin-film solar cell technology accounts for about 10 percent of global photovoltaic deployment.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In recent years, PV technology has improved its sunlight to electricity conversion efficiency, reduced the installation cost per watt as well as its energy payback time (EPBT) and levelised cost of electricity (LCOE), and has reached grid parity in at least 19 different markets in 2014.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] As most renewable energy sources and unlike coal and nuclear, solar PV is variable and non-dispatchable, but has no fuel costs, operating pollution, as well as greatly reduced mining-safety and operating-safety issues.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] It produces peak power around local noon each day and its capacity factor is around 20 percent.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Wind turbines can be distributed energy resources or they can be built at utility scale.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] These have low maintenance and low pollution, but distributed wind unlike utility-scale wind has much higher costs than other sources of energy.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] As with solar, wind energy is variable and non-dispatchable.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Wind towers and generators have substantial insurable liabilities caused by high winds, but good operating safety.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed generation from wind hybrid power systems combines wind power with other DER systems.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] One such example is the integration of wind turbines into solar hybrid power systems, as wind tends to complement solar because the peak operating times for each system occur at different times of the day and year.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Hydroelectricity is the most widely used form of renewable energy and its potential has already been explored to a large extent or is compromised due to issues such as environmental impacts on fisheries, and increased demand for recreational access.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] However, using modern 21st century technology, such as wave power, can make large amounts of new hydropower capacity available, with minor environmental impact.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Modular and scalable *Next generation kinetic energy turbines* can be deployed in arrays to serve the needs on a residential, commercial, industrial, municipal or even regional scale.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] *Microhydro kinetic generators* neither require dams nor impoundments, as they utilize the kinetic energy of water motion, either waves or flow.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] No construction is needed on the shoreline or sea bed, which minimizes environmental impacts to habitats and simplifies the permitting process.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Such power generation also has minimal environmental impact and non-traditional microhydro applications can be tethered to existing construction such as docks, piers, bridge abutments, or similar structures.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Municipal solid waste (MSW) and natural waste, such as sewage sludge, food waste and animal manure will decompose and discharge methane-containing gas that can be collected and used as fuel in gas turbines or micro turbines to produce electricity as a distributed energy resource.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Additionally, a California-based company, Gate 5 Energy Partners, Inc. has developed a process that transforms natural waste materials, such as sewage sludge, into biofuel that can be combusted to power a steam turbine that produces power.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This power can be used in lieu of grid-power at the waste source (such as a treatment plant, farm or dairy).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A distributed energy resource is not limited to the generation of electricity but may also include a device to store distributed energy (DE).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Distributed energy storage systems (DESS) applications include several types of battery, pumped hydro, compressed air, and thermal energy storage.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Access to energy storage for commercial applications is easily accessible through programs such as energy storage as a service (ESaaS).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Compared to the other types, lead-acid batteries have a shorter lifetime and lower energy density.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] (4–6% per year) as well as low investment and maintenance costs, they are currently the predominant technology used in small-scale, residential PV systems, as lithium-ion batteries are still being developed and about 3.5 times as expensive as lead-acid batteries.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] may serve as future storage devices, since most vehicles are parked an average of 95 percent of the time, their batteries could be used to let electricity flow from the car to the power lines and back.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] ) to a very high speed of about 20,000 to over 50,000 rpm in a vacuum enclosure.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Flywheels can respond quickly as they store and feed back electricity into the grid in a matter of seconds.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] For reasons of reliability, distributed generation resources would be interconnected to the same transmission grid as central stations.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Various technical and economic issues occur in the integration of these resources into a grid.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Technical problems arise in the areas of power quality, voltage stability, harmonics, reliability, protection, and control.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Behavior of protective devices on the grid must be examined for all combinations of distributed and central station generation.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A large scale deployment of distributed generation may affect grid-wide functions such as frequency control and allocation of reserves.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] As a result, smart grid functions, virtual power plants and grid energy storage such as power to gas stations are added to the grid.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Conflicts occur between utilities and resource managing organizations.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Each distributed generation resource has its own integration issues.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Solar PV and wind power both have intermittent and unpredictable generation, so they create many stability issues for voltage and frequency.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] These voltage issues affect mechanical grid equipment, such as load tap changers, which respond too often and wear out much more quickly than utilities anticipated.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Also, without any form of energy storage during times of high solar generation, companies must rapidly increase generation around the time of sunset to compensate for the loss of solar generation.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This high ramp rate produces what the industry terms the *duck curve* that is a major concern for grid operators in the future.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Storage can fix these issues if it can be implemented.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Flywheels have shown to provide excellent frequency regulation.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Also, flywheels are highly cyclable compared to batteries, meaning they maintain the same energy and power after a significant amount of cycles( on the order of 10,000 cycles).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Short term use batteries, at a large enough scale of use, can help to flatten the duck curve and prevent generator use fluctuation and can help to maintain voltage profile.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] However, cost is a major limiting factor for energy storage as each technique is prohibitively expensive to produce at scale and comparatively not energy dense compared to liquid fossil fuels.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Finally, another method of aiding in integration is in the use of intelligent inverters that have the capability to also store the energy when there is more energy production than consumption.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] There have been some efforts to mitigate voltage and frequency issues due to increased implementation of DG.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Most notably, IEEE 1547 sets the standard for interconnection and interoperability of distributed energy resources.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] IEEE 1547 sets specific curves signaling when to clear a fault as a function of the time after the disturbance and the magnitude of the voltage irregularity or frequency irregularity.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Voltage issues also give legacy equipment the opportunity to perform new operations.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Notably, inverters can regulate the voltage output of DGs.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Changing inverter impedances can change voltage fluctuations of DG, meaning inverters have the ability to control DG voltage output.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] To reduce the effect of DG integration on mechanical grid equipment, transformers and load tap changers have the potential to implement specific tap operation vs. voltage operation curves mitigating the effect of voltage irregularities due to DG.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] That is, load tap changers respond to voltage fluctuations that last for a longer period than voltage fluctuations created from DG equipment.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] It is now possible to combine technologies such as photovoltaics, batteries and cogeneration to make stand alone distributed generation systems.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Recent work has shown that such systems have a low levelized cost of electricity.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Many authors now think that these technologies may enable a mass-scale grid defection because consumers can produce electricity using off grid systems primarily made up of solar photovoltaic technology.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] For example, the Rocky Mountain Institute has proposed that there may wide scale grid defection.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This is backed up by studies in the Midwest.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Cogenerators find favor because most buildings already burn fuels, and the cogeneration can extract more value from the fuel.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Local production has no electricity transmission losses on long distance power lines or energy losses from the Joule effect in transformers where in general 8-15% of the energy is lost (see also cost of electricity by source).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Some larger installations utilize combined cycle generation.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Usually this consists of a gas turbine whose exhaust boils water for a steam turbine in a Rankine cycle.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The condenser of the steam cycle provides the heat for space heating or an absorptive chiller.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Combined cycle plants with cogeneration have the highest known thermal efficiencies, often exceeding 85%.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In countries with high pressure gas distribution, small turbines can be used to bring the gas pressure to domestic levels whilst extracting useful energy.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] If the UK were to implement this countrywide an additional 2-4 GWe would become available.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A *microgrid* is a localized grouping of electricity generation, energy storage, and loads that normally operates connected to a traditional centralized grid (macrogrid).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This single point of common coupling with the macrogrid can be disconnected.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The microgrid can then function autonomously.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Generation and loads in a microgrid are usually interconnected at low voltage and it can operate in DC, AC, or the combination of both.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] From the point of view of the grid operator, a connected microgrid can be controlled as if it were one entity.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Microgrid generation resources can include stationary batteries, fuel cells, solar, wind, or other energy sources.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The multiple dispersed generation sources and ability to isolate the microgrid from a larger network would provide highly reliable electric power.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Produced heat from generation sources such as microturbines could be used for local process heating or space heating, allowing flexible trade off between the needs for heat and electric power.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Micro-grids have seen implementation in a number of communities over the world.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] For example, Tesla has implemented a solar micro-grid in the Samoan island of Ta'u, powering the entire island with solar energy.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This localized production system has helped save over 380 cubic metres (100,000 US gal) of diesel fuel.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] It is also able to sustain the island for three whole days if the sun were not to shine at all during that period.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] This is a great example of how micro-grid systems can be implemented in communities to encourage renewable resource usage and localized production.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] To plan and install Microgrids correctly, engineering modelling is needed.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Multiple simulation tools and optimization tools exist to model the economic and electric effects of Microgrids.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A widely used economic optimization tool is the Distributed Energy Resources Customer Adoption Model (DER-CAM) from Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] Another frequently used commercial economic modelling tool is Homer Energy, originally designed by the National Renewable Laboratory.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] There are also some power flow and electrical design tools guiding the Microgrid developers.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The Pacific Northwest National Laboratory designed the public available GridLAB-D tool and the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) designed OpenDSS to simulate the distribution system (for Microgrids).
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A professional integrated DER-CAM and OpenDSS version is available via BankableEnergy Archived 11 July 2018 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] A European tool that can be used for electrical, cooling, heating, and process heat demand simulation is EnergyPLAN from the Aalborg University, Denmark.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] In 2010 Colorado enacted a law requiring that by 2020 that 3% of the power generated in Colorado utilize distributed generation of some sort.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] On 11 October 2017, California Governor Jerry Brown signed into law a bill, SB 338, that makes utility companies plan "carbon-free alternatives to gas generation" in order to meet peak demand.
[src:microgrid-control/distributed-generation] The law requires utilities to evaluate issues such as energy storage, efficiency, and distributed energy resources.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] This mode allows synchronous generators to run in parallel, so that loads are shared among generators with the same droop curve in proportion to their power rating.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] In practice, the droop curves that are used by generators on large electrical grids are not necessarily linear or the same, and may be adjusted by operators.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] This permits the ratio of power used to vary depending on load so that, for example, base load generators will generate a larger proportion at low demand.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Stability requires that over the operating frequency range the power output is a monotonically decreasing function of frequency.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Droop speed control can also be used by grid storage systems.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] With droop speed control those systems will remove energy from the grid at higher than average frequencies, and supply it at lower frequencies.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] The frequency (F) of a synchronous generator is directly proportional to its speed (N).
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] When multiple synchronous generators are connected in parallel to the electrical grid, the frequency is fixed by the grid, since individual power output of each generator will be small compared to the load on a large grid.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Synchronous generators connected to the grid all run at the same frequency but they can run at various speeds because they can differ in the number of poles (P).
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] A speed reference as percentage of actual speed is set in this mode.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] As the generator is loaded from no load to full load, the actual speed of the prime mover tends to decrease.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] In order to increase the power output in this mode, the prime mover speed reference is increased.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Because the actual prime mover speed is fixed by the grid, this difference in speed reference and actual speed of the prime mover is used to increase the flow of working fluid (fuel, steam, etc.) to the prime mover, and hence power output is increased.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] The reverse will be true for decreasing power output.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] The prime mover speed reference is always greater than actual speed of the prime mover.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] The actual speed of the prime mover is allowed to "droop" or decrease with respect to the reference, and so the name.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] In this case, speed reference will be 104% and actual speed will be 100%.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] For every 1% change in the turbine speed reference, the power output of the turbine will change by 25% of rated for a unit with a 4% droop setting.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Droop is therefore expressed as the percentage change in (design) speed required for 100% governor action.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] As frequency is fixed on the grid, and so actual turbine speed is also fixed, the increase in turbine speed reference will increase the error between reference and actual speed.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] As the difference increases, fuel flow is increased to increase power output, and vice versa.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] This type of control is referred to as "straight proportional" control.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] If the entire grid tends to be overloaded, the grid frequency and hence actual speed of generator will decrease.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] All units will see an increase in the speed error, and so increase fuel flow to their prime movers and power output.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] In this way droop speed control mode also helps to hold a stable grid frequency.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] The amount of power produced is strictly proportional to the error between the actual turbine speed and speed reference.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] It can be mathematically shown that if all machines synchronized to a system have the same droop speed control, they will share load proportionate to the machine ratings.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] The above formula is nothing but the equation of a straight line (y = mx + b).
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Multiple synchronous generators having equal % droop setting connected to a grid will share the change in grid load in proportion of their base load.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] For stable operation of the electrical grid of North America, power plants typically operate with a four or five percent speed droop.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] By definition, with 5% droop the full-load speed is 100% and the no-load speed is 105%.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Normally the changes in speed are minor due to inertia of the total rotating mass of all generators and motors running on the grid.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Adjustments in power output for a particular prime mover and generator combination are made by slowly raising the droop curve by increasing the spring pressure on a centrifugal governor or by an engine control unit adjustment, or the analogous operation for an electronic speed governor.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] All units to be connected to a grid should have the same droop setting, so that all plants respond in the same way to the instantaneous changes in frequency without depending on outside communication.
[src:microgrid-control/droop-speed-control] Next to the inertia given by the parallel operation of synchronous generators, the frequency speed droop is the primary instantaneous parameter in control of an individual power plant's power output (kW).
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Intentional islanding is often performed as a defence in depth to mitigate a cascading blackout.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] If one island collapses, it will not take neighboring islands with it.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] For example, nuclear power plants have safety-critical cooling systems that are typically powered from the general grid.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] The coolant loops typically lie on a separate circuit that can also operate off reactor power or emergency diesel generators if the grid collapses.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Grid designs that lend themselves to islanding near the customer level are commonly referred to as microgrids.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] In a power outage, the microgrid controller disconnects the local circuit from the grid on a dedicated switch and forces any online distributed generators to power the local load.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Unintentional islanding is a dangerous condition that may induce severe stress on the generator, as the generator must match any changes in electrical load alone.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] If not properly communicated to power line workers, an unintentional island can also present a risk of electrical shock.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Unlike unpowered wires, islands require special techniques to reconnect to the larger grid, because the alternating current they carry is not in phase.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] For these reasons, solar inverters that are designed to supply power to the grid are generally required to have some sort of automatic anti-islanding circuitry, which shorts out the panels rather than continuing to power the unintentional island.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Methods that detect islands without a large number of false positives constitute the subject of considerable research.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Each method has some threshold that needs to be crossed before a condition is considered to be a signal of grid interruption, which leads to a "**non-detection zone**" (NDZ), the range of conditions where a real grid failure will be filtered out.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] For this reason, before field deployment, grid-interactive inverters are typically tested by reproducing at their output terminals specific grid conditions and evaluating the effectiveness of the anti-islanding methods in detecting island conditions.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Intentional islanding divides an electrical network into fragments with adequate power generation in each fragment to supply that fragment's loads.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] In practice, balancing generation and load in each fragment is difficult, and often the formation of islands requires temporarily shedding load.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Synchronous generators may not deliver sufficient reactive power to prevent severe transients during fault-induced island formation, and any inverters must switch from constant-current to constant-voltage control.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Intentional islanding can be used after a blackout and during the black start process to restore power to isolated parts of the grid.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Assuming P≠NP, no good cut set criterion exists to implement islanding.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Polynomial-time approximations exist, but finding the exactly optimal divisions can be computationally infeasible.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] However, islanding localizes any failures to the containing island, preventing failures from spreading.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] In general, blackout statistics follow a power law, such that fragmenting a network increases the probability of blackouts, but reduces the total amount of unsatisfied electricity demand.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Islanding reduces the economic efficiency of the wholesale power market, and is typically a last resort applied when the grid is known to be unstable but has not yet collapsed.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] In particular, islanding improves resilience to threats with known time but not location, such as terrorist attacks, military strikes on electrical infrastructure, or extreme weather events.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Following the 2019 California power shutoffs, there was a rise in interest in the possibility of operating a house's electrical grid as an island.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] While typical distributed generation systems are too small to power all appliances in a home simultaneously, it is possible for them to manage critical household power needs through traditional load-frequency control.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Modules installed in series between the generator and large loads, like air conditioners and electric ovens, measure the island power frequency and perform automatic load shedding as the inverter nears overload.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Automatically detecting an island is the subject of considerable research.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] These can be performed passively, looking for transient events on the grid; or actively, by creating small instances of those transient events that will be negligible on a large grid but detectable on a small one.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Active methods may be performed by local generators or "upstream" at the utility level.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Many passive methods rely on the inherent stress of operating an island.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Each device in the island comprises a much larger proportion of the total load, such that the voltage and frequency changes as devices are added or removed are likely to be much larger than in normal grid conditions.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] However, the difference is not so large as to prevent identification errors, and voltage and frequency shifts are generally used along with other signals.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] The active analogue of voltage and frequency shift detection attempts to measure the overall impedance fed by the inverter.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] When the circuit is grid-connected, there is almost no voltage response to slight variations in inverter current; but an island will observe a change in voltage.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] In principle, this technique has a vanishingly small NDZ, but in practice the grid is not always an infinitely-stiff voltage source, especially if multiple inverters attempt to measure impedance simultaneously.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Unlike the shifts, a random circuit is highly unlikely to have a characteristic frequency matching standard grid power.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] However, many devices, like televisions, deliberately synchronize to the grid frequency.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Motors, in particular, may be able to stabilize circuit frequency close to the grid standard as they "wind down".
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] At the utility level, protective relays designed to isolate a portion of the grid can also switch in high impedance components, such that an islanded distributed generator will necessarily overload and shut down.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] This practice, however, relies on the expensive widespread provision of high-impedance devices.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Alternatively, anti-islanding circuitry can rely on out-of-band signals.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] For example, utilities can send a shut-down signal through power line carrier communications or a telephony hookup.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Certain passive methods are uniquely viable with direct current generators (inverter-based resources), such as solar panels.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] For example, inverters typically generate a phase shift when islanding.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Inverters generally match the grid signal with a phase locked loop (PLL) that tracks zero-crossings.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Between those events, the inverter produces a sinusoidal output, varying the current to produce the proper voltage waveform given the previous cycle's load.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] When the main grid disconnects, the power factor on the island suddenly decreases, and inverter's current no longer produces the proper waveform.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] By the time the waveform is completed and returns to zero, the signal will be out of phase.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] However, many common events, like motors starting, also cause phase jumps as new impedances are added to the circuit.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] A more effective technique inverts the islanding phase shift: the inverter is designed to produce output slightly mis-aligned with the grid, with the expectation that the grid will overwhelm the signal.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] The phase-locked loop then becomes unstable when the grid signal is missing; the system drifts away from the design frequency; and the inverter shuts down.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] A very secure islanding detection method searches for distinctive 2nd and 3rd harmonics generated by nonlinear interactions inside the inverter transformers.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] There are generally no other total harmonic distortion (THD) sources that match an inverter.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Even noisy sources, like motors, do not effect measurable distortion on a grid-connected circuit, as the latter has essentially infinite filtration capacity.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Switched-mode inverters generally have large distortions — as much as 5%.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] When the grid disconnects, the local circuit then exhibits inverter-induced distortion.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Modern inverters attempt to minimize harmonic distortion, in some cases to unmeasurable limits, but in principle it is straightforward to design one which introduces a controlled amount of distortion to actively search for island formation.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Utilities have refused to allow installation of home solar or other distributed generation systems, on the grounds that they may create uncontrolled grid islands.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] In Ontario, a 2009 modification to the feed-in tariff induced many rural customers to establish small (10 kW) systems under the "capacity exempt" microFIT.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] However, Hydro One then refused to connect the systems to the grid after construction.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] The issue can be hotly political, in part because distributed generation proponents believe the islanding concern is largely pretextual.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] A 1999 test in the Netherlands was unable to find distributed-generation islands 60 seconds after grid collapse.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Moreover, moments when distributed generation only matched distributed loads occurred at a rate comparable to 10−6 yr−1, and that the chance that the grid would disconnect at that point in time was even less, so that the "probability of encountering an islanding [*sic*] is virtually zero".
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Unintentional islanding risk is primarily the case of synchronous generators, as in microhydro.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] If an island forms, repair crews may be faced with unexpected live wires.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] close to standard, and nonstandard currents can damage customer equipment.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Depending on the circuit configuration, the utility may be liable for the damage.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Procedures to prevent these outcomes may delay restoration of electric service to dropped customers.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] The first two claims are disputed within the power industry.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] For example, normal linework constantly risks exposure to live wires, and standard procedures require explicit checks to ensure that a wire is dead before worker contact.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) systems can be set to alarm if there is unexpected voltage on a purportedly-isolated line.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] It is, generally, the last problem that most concerns utilities.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] Reclosers are commonly used to divide up the grid into smaller sections that will automatically, and quickly, re-energize the branch as soon as the fault condition (a tree branch on lines for instance) clears.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] There is some concern that the reclosers may not re-energize in the case of an island or that an intervening loss of synchrony might damage distributed generators on the island.
[src:microgrid-control/islanding] However, it is neither clear that reclosers are still useful in modern utility practice nor that breaker-reclosers must act on all phases.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A **microgrid** is a local electrical grid with defined electrical boundaries, acting as a single and controllable entity.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] It is able to operate in grid-connected and off-grid modes.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Microgrids may be linked as a cluster or operated as **stand-alone** or **isolated microgrid** which only operates off-the-grid not be connected to a wider electric power system.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Very small microgrids are sometimes called nanogrids when they serve a single building or load.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A grid-connected microgrid normally operates connected to and synchronous with the traditional wide area synchronous grid (macrogrid), but is able to disconnect from the interconnected grid and to function autonomously in "island mode" as technical or economic conditions dictate.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In this way, they improve the security of supply within the microgrid cell, and can supply emergency power, changing between island and connected modes.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This kind of grid is called an **islandable microgrid**.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] One version of a microgrid implements control of small-scale distributed generation (DG) at a single house/small building level: the **nanogrid**.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Modular open-source hardware DC nanogrids have been developed to provide solar photovoltaic power for any small-scale system such as an ambulance or even down the device level.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Although DC systems generally are more efficient, nanogrids can also be AC to make them compatible with more mainstream devices.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A stand-alone microgrid has its own sources of electricity, supplemented with an energy storage system.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] They are used where power transmission and distribution from a major centralized energy source is too far and costly to operate.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] They offer an option for rural electrification in remote areas and on smaller geographical islands.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A stand-alone microgrid can effectively integrate various sources of distributed generation, especially renewable energy sources (RES).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Control and protection are difficulties to microgrids, as all ancillary services for system stabilization must be generated within the microgrid and low short-circuit levels can be challenging for selective operation of the protection systems.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The United States Department of Energy Microgrid Exchange Group defines a microgrid as "a group of interconnected loads and distributed energy resources within clearly defined electrical boundaries that acts as a single controllable entity with respect to the grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] An EU research project describes a microgrid as comprising Low-Voltage (LV) distribution systems with distributed energy resources (DERs) (microturbines, fuel cells, photovoltaics (PV), etc.), storage devices (batteries, flywheels) energy storage system and flexible loads.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Such systems can operate either connected or disconnected from the main grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The operation of microsources in the network can provide benefits to the overall system performance, if managed and coordinated efficiently.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Electropedia defines a microgrid as a group of interconnected loads and distributed energy resources with defined electrical boundaries, which form a local electric power system at distribution voltage levels, meaning both low and medium voltage up to 35 kV.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This cluster of associated consumer and producer nodes acts as a single controllable entity and is able to operate in either grid-connected or island mode.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A stand-alone microgrid or isolated microgrid, sometimes called an "island grid", only operates off-the-grid and cannot be connected to a wider electric power system.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] They are usually designed for geographical islands or for rural electrification.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In many non-industrialized countries, microgrids that are used to provide access to electricity in previously unelectrified areas are often referred to as "mini grids".
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Nanogrids belong to a single home or building and the interconnection of multiple nanogrids forming a network (microgrid), facilitating the sharing of power between individual nanogrids.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The focus of campus microgrids is aggregating existing on-site generation to support multiple loads located in a tight geographical area where an owner can easily manage them.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Community microgrids can serve thousands of customers and support the penetration of local energy (electricity, heating, and cooling).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In a community microgrid, some houses may have some renewable sources that can supply their demand as well as that of their neighbors within the same community.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The community microgrid may also have a centralized or several distributed energy storages.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Such microgrids can be in the form of an ac and dc microgrid coupled together through a bi-directional power electronic converter.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] These microgrids are generally not designed or intended to connect to the macrogrid and instead operate in an island mode at all times because of economic issues or geographical position.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Typically, an "off-grid" microgrid is built in areas that are far distant from any transmission and distribution infrastructure and, therefore, have no connection to the utility grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Studies have demonstrated that operating a remote area or islands' off-grid microgrids, that are dominated by renewable sources, will reduce the levelized cost of electricity production over the life of such microgrid projects.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In some cases, off-grid microgrids are indeed incorporated into a national grid or 'macrogrid', a process that requires technical, regulatory and legal planning.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Large remote areas may be supplied by several independent microgrids, each with a different owner (operator).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Although such microgrids are traditionally designed to be energy self-sufficient, intermittent renewable sources and their unexpected and sharp variations can cause unexpected power shortfall or excessive generation in those microgrids.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Without energy storage and smart controls, this will immediately cause unacceptable voltage or frequency deviation in the microgrids.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] To remedy such situations, it is possible to interconnect such microgrids provisionally to a suitable neighboring microgrid to exchange power and improve the voltage and frequency deviations.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This can be achieved through a power electronics-based switch after a proper synchronization or a back to back connection of two power electronic converters and after confirming the stability of the new system.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The determination of a need to interconnect neighboring microgrids and finding the suitable microgrid to couple with can be achieved through optimization or decision making approaches.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Because remote off-grid microgrids are often small and built from scratch, they have the potential to incorporate best practices from the global electricity sector and to incorporate and drive energy innovation.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] It is now common to see remote off-grid microgrids being largely powered by renewable energy and operated with customer-level smart controls, something that is not always easy to implement in the larger power sector because of incumbent interests and older, pre-existing infrastructure.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] These microgrids are being actively deployed with focus on both physical and cyber security for military facilities in order to assure reliable power without relying on the macrogrid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] These types of microgrids are maturing quickly in North America and eastern Asia; however, the lack of well-known standards for these types of microgrids limits them globally.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Main reasons for the installation of an industrial microgrid are power supply security and its reliability.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] There are many manufacturing processes in which an interruption of the power supply may cause high revenue losses and long start-up time.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Microgrids can also be anchored by a large commercial retailer with a large quantity of generation for resiliency or economic reasons.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Architectures are needed to manage the flow of energy from different types of sources into the electrical grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Power sources with AC output are interfaced to AC bus through AC/AC converter which will transform the AC variable frequency and voltage to AC waveform with another frequency at another voltage.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Whilst power sources with DC output use DC/AC converters for the connection to the AC bus.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In DC microgrid topology, power sources with DC output are connected to DC bus directly or by DC/DC converters.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] On the other hand, power sources with AC output are connected to the DC bus through AC/DC converter.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The hybrid microgrid has topology for both power source AC and DC output.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In addition, AC and DC buses are connected to each other through a bidirectional converter, allowing power to flow in both directions between the two buses.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A microgrid presents various types of generation sources that feed electricity, heating, and cooling to the user.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] These sources are include gaseous fuels such as natural gas, biogas or hydrogen typically as [gas engines] in combined heat and power (CHP) or combined cooling heat and power (CCHP) configuration and/or intermittent renewable generation sources such as wind turbines or solar PV units.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In a microgrid, consumption simply refers to elements that consume electricity, heat, and cooling, which range from single devices to the lighting and heating systems of buildings, commercial centers, etc.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In the case of controllable loads, electricity consumption can be modified according to the demands of the network.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In a microgrid, energy storage performs multiple functions, such as ensuring power quality, performing frequency and voltage regulation, smoothing the output of renewable energy sources, providing backup power for the system, and playing a crucial role in cost optimization.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Energy storage may be achieved by a combination of chemical, electrical, pressure, gravitational, flywheel, and heat storage technologies.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] When multiple energy storage devices with various capacities are available in a microgrid, it is preferred to coordinate their charging and discharging such that a smaller energy storage device does not discharge faster than those with larger capacities.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Likewise, it is preferred that a smaller storage device does not get fully charged before those with larger capacities.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This can be achieved under a coordinated control of energy storage devices based on their state of charge.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This is the point in the electric circuit where a microgrid is connected to a main grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Microgrids that do not have a PCC are called isolated microgrids which are usually present in remote sites (e.g., remote communities or remote industrial sites) where an interconnection with the main grid is not feasible due to either technical or economic constraints.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A microgrid is capable of operating in grid-connected and stand-alone modes and of handling the transition between the two.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In the grid-connected mode, ancillary services can be provided by trading activity between the microgrid and the main grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In the islanded mode, the real and reactive power generated within the microgrid, including that provided by the energy storage system, should be in balance with the demand of local loads.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Microgrids offer an option to balance the need to reduce carbon emissions with continuing to provide reliable electric energy in periods of time when renewable sources of power are not available.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Microgrids also offer the security of being hardened from severe weather and natural disasters by not having large assets and miles of above-ground wires and other electric infrastructure that need to be maintained or repaired following such events.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A microgrid may transition between these two modes because of scheduled maintenance, degraded power quality or a shortage in the host grid, faults in the local grid, or for economical reasons.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] By means of modifying energy flow through microgrid components, microgrids facilitate the integration of renewable energy, such as photovoltaic, wind and fuel cell generations, without requiring re-design of the national distribution system.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Modern optimization methods can also be incorporated into the microgrid energy management system to improve efficiency, economics, and resiliency.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Some of these challenges arise from assumptions typically applied to conventional distribution systems that are no longer valid, while others are the result of stability issues formerly observed only at a transmission system level.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A comprehensive commercial platform is XENDEE which won the 2021 Edison Gold Award and is the standard platform for the US Department of Defense.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Another is HOMER (Hybrid Optimization Model for Multiple Energy Resources), originally developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] There are also some power flow and electrical design tools guiding microgrid developers.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The Pacific Northwest National Laboratory designed the publicly available GridLAB-D tool and the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) designed OpenDSS.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A European tool that can be used for electrical, cooling, heating, and process heat demand simulation is EnergyPLAN from Aalborg University in Denmark.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The open source grid planning tool OnSSET has been deployed to investigate microgrids using a three‑tier analysis beginning with settlement archetypes (case‑studied using Bolivia).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In regards to the architecture of microgrid control, or any control problem, there are two different approaches that can be identified: centralized and decentralized.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A fully centralized control relies on a large amount of information transmittance between involving units before a decision is made at a single point.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Implementation is difficult since interconnected power systems usually cover extended geographic locations and involve an enormous number of units.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] On the other hand, in a fully decentralized control, each unit is controlled by its local controller without knowing the situation of others.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A compromise between those two extreme control schemes can be achieved by means of a hierarchical control scheme consisting of three control levels: primary, secondary, and tertiary.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The primary control provides the setpoints for a lower controller which are the voltage and current control loops of DERs.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] These inner control loops are commonly referred to as zero-level control.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Secondary control has typically seconds to minutes sampling time (i.e. slower than the previous one) which justifies the decoupled dynamics of the primary and the secondary control loops and facilitates their individual designs.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The setpoint of primary control is given by secondary control in which, as a centralized controller, it restores the microgrid voltage and frequency and compensates for the deviations caused by variations of loads or renewable sources.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The secondary control can also be designed to satisfy the power quality requirements, e.g., voltage balancing at critical buses.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Tertiary control is the last (and the slowest) control level, which considers economical concerns in the optimal operation of the microgrid (sampling time is from minutes to hours), and manages the power flow between microgrid and main grid.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This level often involves the prediction of weather, grid tariff, and loads in the next hours or day to design a generator dispatch plan that achieves economic savings.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] More advanced techniques can also provide end to end control of a microgrid using machine learning techniques such as deep reinforcement learning.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In case of emergencies such as blackouts, tertiary control can manage a group of interconnected microgrids to form what is called "microgrid clustering", acting as a virtual power plant to continue supplying critical loads.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] During these situations the central controller should select one of the microgrids to be the slack (i.e. master) and the rest as PV and load buses according to a predefined algorithm and the existing conditions of the system (i.e. demand and generation).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] In this case, the control should be real time or at least at a high sampling rate.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A less utility-influenced controller framework is that from the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, the IEEE 2030.7.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A wide variety of complex control algorithms exist, making it difficult for small microgrids and residential distributed energy resource (DER) users to implement energy management and control systems.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Communication upgrades and data information systems can be expensive.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Some projects try to simplify and reduce the expense of control via off-the-shelf products (e.g. using a Raspberry Pi).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A zero-emission microgrid serving roughly 5,000 people in Calistoga, Napa County, California.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The distribution-level microgrid infrastructure is owned by utility, Pacific Gas & Electric Company, and is powered by the Calistoga Resiliency Center facility.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The facility is a First of a Kind commercial-scale project coupling a lithium-ion battery energy storage system (BESS) with onsite liquid hydrogen and hydrogen fuel cells to power Calistoga for up to 48 hours.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The UNDP project "Enhanced Rural Resilience in Yemen" (ERRY) uses community-owned solar microgrids.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] It cuts energy costs to just 2 cents per hour (whereas diesel-generated electricity costs 42 cents per hour).
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] It won the Ashden Awards for Humanitarian Energy in 2020.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A two-year pilot program, called Harmon'Yeu, was initiated in the spring of 2020 to interconnect 23 houses in the Ker Pissot neighborhood and surrounding areas with a microgrid that was automated as a smart grid with software from Engie.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Sixty-four solar panels with a peak capacity of 23.7 kW were installed on five houses and a battery with a storage capacity of 15 kWh was installed on one house.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Six houses store excess solar energy in their hot water heaters.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A dynamic system apportions the energy provided by the solar panels and stored in the battery and hot water heaters to the system of 23 houses.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The smart grid software dynamically updates energy supply and demand in 5-minute intervals, deciding whether to pull energy from the battery or from the panels and when to store it in the hot water heaters.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] This pilot program was the first such project in France.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A wirelessly managed microgrid is deployed in rural Les Anglais, Haiti.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The system consists of a three-tiered architecture with a cloud-based monitoring and control service, a local embedded gateway infrastructure and a mesh network of wireless smart meters deployed at over 500 buildings.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Non-technical loss (NTL) represents a major challenge when providing reliable electrical service in developing countries, where it often accounts for 11-15% of total generation capacity.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] An extensive data-driven simulation on seventy-two days of wireless meter data from a 430-home microgrid deployed in Les Anglais investigated how to distinguish NTL from the total power losses, aiding in energy theft detection.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] The Mpeketoni Electricity Project, a community-based diesel-powered micro-grid system, was set up in rural Kenya near Mpeketoni.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Due to the installment of these microgrids, Mpeketoni has seen a large growth in its infrastructure.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Such growth includes increased productivity per worker, at values of 100% to 200%, and an income level increase of 20–70% depending on the product.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] A micro-turbine, fuel-cell, multiple battery, hydrogen electrolyzer, and PV enabled winery in Sonoma, California.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] Near Lake Havasu, Arizona, extreme weather, power disruptions due to aging infrastructure, and distance from the main power grid put the community of the Chemehuevi Tribe at risk.
[src:microgrid-control/microgrid] To mitigate that risk, a microgrid system was built on the tribal community center integrating solar panels, battery storage, smart energy management controls, and advanced data analytics in conjunction with a weather station.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A **virtual power plant** (**VPP**) is a system for aggregating distributed energy resources (DERs) to function as a single power plant.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Operators coordinate these resources to balance supply and demand, provide grid services, and participate in energy markets.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A VPP typically sells its output to an electric utility.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs allow energy resources that are individually too small to be of interest to a utility to aggregate and market their power.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs typically access dispatchable and non-dispatchable resources, including microCHPs, natural gas-fired reciprocating engines, wind power plants, photovoltaics (PV), run-of-river hydroelectricity, biomass, backup generators, battery energy storage systems (BESS) such as home or vehicle batteries.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs can manage demand as well as supply; e.g., heat pumps and other devices can be turned on or off based on available energy supply.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Heterogeneity and numbers reduce dependence on any single resource, improving system stability.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Vehicle-to-grid allows grid-connected electric vehicles to participate.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Storage-based VPPs ramp faster than thermal generators, e.g., helping grids with high ramp needs avoid the duck curve.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A management system securely controls operations, billing, and payments to power suppliers and consumers.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs provide peak shaving by delivering power during high demand, avoiding expensive peaker plants (saving 40–60%).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] They offer load following and ancillary services such as frequency regulation and operating reserves, responding in seconds to minutes.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs can trade energy in wholesale markets, acting as dispatchable plants.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Shimon Awerbuch proposed the VPP concept in 1997.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Early work remained theoretical due to technology and regulatory limits.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Papers in the early 2000s examined renewable aggregation.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Challenges included communication costs and risks.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] RWE launched the first VPP in 2008, aggregating nine hydroelectric plants for 8.6 MW.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The University of Kassel piloted one linking solar, wind, biogas, and hydroelectricity for load following.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Kraftwerke started in 2011, expanding across seven countries, aggregating biogas, solar, and wind.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] In the United States, VPPs built on demand response programs.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The 2009 American Recovery and Reinvestment Act supported smart grids.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Federal Energy Regulatory Commission Order 745 (2011) treated demand reductions as generation in wholesale markets.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Order 2222 (2020) enabled direct DER bidding.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] AGL Energy started a 5 MW VPP in Adelaide in 2016 with batteries and PV for 1,000 homes.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Tesla opened a VPP in South Australia in 2018, reaching 50,000 homes by 2022; AGL acquired the program in 2025, reaching 25 MW solar and 37 MW storage.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] UK Power Networks and Powervault launched London's first VPP in 2018 (0.32 MWh); Tesla partnered with Octopus Energy there in 2020.created London's first VPP in 2018, installing BESS at 40+ homes across Barnet, with capacity of 0.32 MWh, expanding it in 2020.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] In 2019, SMS plc launched a VPP following the acquisition of Irish firm, Solo Energy.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] In 2020, Tesla launched its Tesla Energy Plan in the UK in partnership with Octopus Energy.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Participant homes are powered with renewable energy either from solar panels or from Octopus Energy.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Tesla operated VPPs in Texas and California.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] In 2024, Enpal and Entrix (via Flexa) planned Europe's largest VPP, targeting 1 GW by 2026 with solar, batteries, and EVs; launch occurred later that year.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Virginia mandated a Dominion Energy VPP pilot (up to 450 MW) in 2025; the utility proposed it by December.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Vermont VPPs saved $3 million during 2025 heat waves.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] North American capacity reached 37.5 GW in 2025.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs typically aggregate large numbers of distributed energy resources (DER).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Resources can be dispatchable or non-dispatchable, controllable or flexible load (CL or FL).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Resources can include micro-CHPs, natural gas-fired reciprocating engines, wind power (WPP), photovoltaics (PV), run-of-river hydroelectricity, small hydro, biomass, backup generators, and BESS, as well as devices whose consumption is adjustable (such as water heaters and appliances).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The numbers and heterogeneity mean that system output is not dependent on any single resource, offering the potential for stable output even if the output of any single resource is not.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Vehicle-to-grid (V2G) technology allows grid-connected EVs to participate in VPPs.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The VPP controls the rate at which each vehicle charges/discharges (accepts/delivers power).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The same principle applies to consuming systems, such as heat pumps or air conditioners that can lower their power demands to reduce demand.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs based on storage can ramp at higher rates than thermal generators (such as fossil fuel plants), which is especially valuable in grids that experience a duck curve and must satisfy high ramping requirements in the morning and evening.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] VPPs can be as dependable as conventional plants, while costing 40–60 percent less.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] One study forecasted that decentralized generation would comprise 500,000 megawatts of capacity compared to centralized generation of 280,000 megawatts.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Power delivery is controlled by a management system.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The distributed nature of VPPs requires software to respond appropriately and securely to power requests, utility billing, payments to resource owners, etc.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Typically, the VPP provides power (only) when requested by the utility.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] With the appropriate resources, a VPP can deliver incremental power on short notice, helping utilities to manage peak loads that would otherwise require purchasing expensive power from a peaker plant (typically powered by natural gas).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Given sufficient scale, a VPP can operate as a load-following generator, supplying output dynamically as demand changes throughout the day/night cycle.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Virtual power plants can provide ancillary services that help maintain grid stability such as frequency regulation and providing operating reserve.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] These services are primarily used to maintain the instantaneous balance of electrical supply and demand.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] These services must respond to signals to increase or decrease load on the order of seconds to minutes.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Electrical energy markets are wholesale, international markets that trade electrical energy.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Market prices fluctuate with demand and supply (e.g., when the wind subsides).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The VPP behaves as a conventional dispatchable power plant from the point of view of other market participants.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A VPP arbitrages between diverse energy markets (e.g., bilateral and purchase power agreements (PPA), forward and futures markets, and the pool).
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] In 2023 the Department of Energy estimated VPP capacity at around 30 to 60 GW, some 4–8% of peak electricity demand.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Eligible Tesla Electric members automatically join the Virtual Power Plant, consisting of Tesla Powerwall batteries.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Tesla pays the owner a monthly fee in addition to payment per unit of energy delivered.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] California has two electric markets: retail and wholesale.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] As of 2022 PG&E paid VPP providers $2/kWh during peak demand.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] As of August/September 2022, SunRun VPP often delivered 80 MW at peak times, while Tesla VPP supplied 68 MW.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] By 2025, California was testing 100,000 residential batteries at a combined 535 MW.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] That amount of electricity can power a mid-sized city.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] It is part of the process to advance the smart grid, where utilities don't just send power to customers but the process is interactive.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Virginia's Virtual Power Plant (VPP) pilot program is a state-mandated initiative requiring Dominion Energy Virginia (a Phase II Utility) to implement a pilot VPP.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] It is to include incentives for 15 MW+ of distributed BESS, including residential, commercial, and industrial customers.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] As of early 2026, the program represented one of the US' largest VPP pilots.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A program for electrification of school buses must be filed by December 31, 2027.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Vermont's Green Mountain Power works with Tesla to offer a Powerwall to participating customers at a discounted rate.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Three Massachusetts utilities, National Grid, Eversource, and Cape Light Compact, operate a VPP.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The Massachusetts Clean Energy Center (MassCEC) is implementing a vehicle‑to‑everything (V2X) demonstration program as part of its VPP that installs free, bi‑directional EV chargers at school districts, municipalities, and residents.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The Institute for Solar Energy Supply Technology of Germany's University of Kassel pilot-tested a VPP that linked solar, wind, biogas, and pumped-storage hydroelectricity to provide load-following power from renewable sources.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A VPP operated on the Scottish Inner Hebrides island of Eigg.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Kraftwerke operates a VPP in seven European countries that provides peak-load resources, power trading and grid balancing.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The company aggregates energy from biogas, solar and wind as well as large-scale power consumers.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] A London VPP is supported by UK Power Networks, and Powervault.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Tesla operates in the UK in partnership with Octopus Energy.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Participant homes are powered with renewable energy from solar panels or from Octopus Energy.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] German companies Enpal and Entrix operate Europe's largest VPP that integrates PV, BESS, and electric vehicles.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] Enpal is a solar installer with more than 70,000 installed systems, connects thousands of solar/BESS households to the VPP.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] AGL Energy operates a 25 MW virtual-power-plant scheme in Adelaide.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The company supplies BESS and photovoltaic systems, to >8,000 customers.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] The systems cost consumers A$3500 with a 7 year payout.
[src:microgrid-control/virtual-power-plant] As of 2025, the program provided 25 MW solar and 37 MW storage.
